Hi, 
First i should mention that blazor is preety awsome and in some aspects is much more convenient than other client side frame work i mean doing
      `if(a){
           <p>true</p>
        }
        else{
              <p>false</p>
       }`
is simpler than *ngIf or the react way tnx to razor, and javascript intrope is really great and else
But in terms of performance it really is 'i have to say' bad
It takes 8 to 11 sec for first time loading even in published project in production mode and 3 to 5 for next reload which most of the time happens instantly in angular or react, also in terms of changing component it still experience huge performance gap, and also it consume lots of resources (cpu) but as i understand wasm should outpreforme js, so i was wondering why it is so weak in performance
Is it because it still is in experimental phase and we should expect huuuuuuuuge performance gain by the time of final realese or not?
Tnx

**Info about the project:**
- Running Blazor 0.5.1, ASP.NET Core 2.1
- Blazor Server-side Project

**Issue:**
So I tried to experiment with the Task.Delay aync/await, and without it. First I tried with the usual way, async Task and then await the Task.Delay. This works fine (But locks the UI thread)

But If I remove the await from Task.Delay, Windows hangs and in the end a force shutdown is required as Windows itself don't respond.

Here's my OnInitAsync code where the Task is executed:

```
protected override async Task OnInitAsync()
    {
        forecasts = await ForecastService.GetForecastAsync(DateTime.Now);
        isRunning = true;

        Task loopTask = Task.Run(() =>
        {
            Random Ran = new Random();
            while (isRunning)
            {
                forecasts.Add(new WeatherForecast()
                {
                    Date = DateTime.Now,
                    Summary = "Bla bla",
                    TemperatureC = Ran.Next(1, 100),
                    TemperatureF = Ran.Next(1, 100)
                });
                Task.Delay(1000);
            }
        });
    }
```

Is the "Hang windows until it basically crashes" an intended feature? Shouldn't something (The Blazor ASP.NET Server) prevent this somehow?
